<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-130-600  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 130 600.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  Feb 1989 v21 n2 p42(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bridging the gap between micro and mainframe.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>One problem with geographic information systems is that oftenmapping agencies cannot begin with a mainframe-based approach,even though a mainframe will ultimately be required.andP;  Instead, theprocess is started on microcomputers for cost-effectiveness.andP;  Atsome point, though, the agencies must make the transition to amainframe-based approach.andP;  This is made difficult by differingoperating systems.andP;  Software Support Ltd, however, says it hassolved this problem by developing a geographic informationprocessing system and phasing in the networking and multitaskingcapabilities of workstations from Sun Microsystems of Canada Inc.andO;Even users who want to begin on workstations instead ofmicrocomputers will benefit from Software Support's system, whichallows users to integrate greater numbers of workstations, providemore I-O power per workstation, and increase multitasking ability.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Software Support Ltd. (products).andO;Topic:     Software MigrationMapsGeographic Information SystemsSoftware DesignCompatible Software.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>